	Calcutta: Gaganjeet Bhullar blasted a blistering seven-under 65 to equal the course record and grab the opening day lead in the PGTI Players Championship at Panchkula Thursday. Bhullar reeled off eight birdies, as against the lone bogey on the sixth hole, to equal Karanjit Singh Sandhus course record.           
	 Madrid: Former world No. 1 Carlos Moya has pulled out of this months Masters Series tournaments at Indian Wells and Miami due to a leg injury.    
	The 32-year-old Spaniard has been troubled by weakness in his right leg for nearly a year and had tests in Miami after his second-round elimination in the Acapulco tournament last month. He will be out indefinitely, agent Benito Perez-Barbadillo said.        
	 Melbourne: Former Australia international Abbas Saad has had his life ban for match-fixing lifted after almost 14 years, freeing him up to coach in Singapore. It was learnt that the Lebanon-born Abbas, 41, was found guilty in 1995 of conspiring with a teammate to fix Singaporean league matches and was given a world ban by the Fifa.         
	New Delhi: The International Hockey Federation (FIH) has dismissed security fears about visiting India following a slew of militant attacks in the region, insisting next years World Cup would be staged in New Delhi as planned. We always listen carefully to our athletes and national associations and take their advice and requests into consideration, said FIHs Arjen Meijer.
                                                                                                                                                                       
